{"title_page": "J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen", "text_new": "[[File:J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen.tif|alt=|thumb|J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen, 2007]]\n'''J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen''' (born 3 October 1934, Copenhagen) is one of Denmark's most eminent sculptors. He had his artistic debut at the acclaimed and prestigious [https://kunsthalcharlottenborg.dk/da/udstillinger/charlottenborg-foraarsudstilling-2020/ Spring Exhibition] (''For\u00e5rsudstillingen'') at [[Kunsthal Charlottenborg]], Copenhagen in 1953. Haugen S\u00f8rensen is a member of the artistic union [https://decembristerne.info Decembristerne] and the artist collective [[Gr\u00f8nningen]], as well as Veks\u00f8lund in Denmark. \n\nThe post-war and contemporary sculptor has been hailed as the greatest Danish sculptor since [[Bertel Thorvaldsen]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Helleland, Allis.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/180194528|title=J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen : a biography|date=2007|publisher=Statens Museum for Kunst|others=Bjerkhof, Sven., Statens museum for kunst (Denmark)|isbn=978-87-92023-03-2|location=[Copenhagen, Denmark]|oclc=180194528}}</ref>. He has received several important distinctions for his works through the years, such as the [[Eckersberg Medal|Eckerberg Medal]] in 1969<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Kunst_og_kultur/Billedkunst/Kunstnere,_danske/J\u00f8rgen_Haugen_S\u00f8rensen|title=J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen {{!}} Gyldendal - Den Store Danske|website=denstoredanske.dk|language=da|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and the [[Thorvaldsen Medal]] in 1979.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Kunst_og_kultur/Billedkunst/Kunstnere,_danske/J\u00f8rgen_Haugen_S\u00f8rensen|title=J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen {{!}} Gyldendal - Den Store Danske|website=denstoredanske.dk|language=da|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> In 1958 he was selected to represent Denmark at the [[Venice Biennale|Biennale di Venezia]].<ref name=Helleland>{{Cite book|last=Helleland|first=Allis|title=J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen : a biography|date=2007|publisher=Statens Museum for Kunst|others=Bjerkhof, Sven., Statens museum for kunst (Denmark)|isbn=978-87-92023-03-2|location=[Copenhagen, Denmark]|oclc=180194528}}</ref> Haugen S\u00f8rensen's sculptures are placed all around the world.<ref name=Helleland/>\n\n==Early life==\nAs a child, together with his brother [[Arne Haugen S\u00f8rensen|Arne]], Haugen S\u00f8rensen began to draw and later to model. When he was 15, he trained as a plasterer and potter and then attended the [[Danmarks Designskole|Design School]] in Copenhagen.  As a sculptor, however, he was self-taught.<ref name=Weilbach>[https://www.kulturarv.dk/kid/VisWeilbach.do?kunstnerId=1056&wsektion=alle Pia Kristine M\u00fcnster, \"J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen\"], ''Kunstindeks Danmark & Weilbachs Kunstnerleksikon''. {{in lang|da}} Retrieved 4 June 2012.</ref>\n\nJ\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen has spent most of his life abroad, living in a voluntary exile in Southern Europe. The 1960s he spent in Paris, France and Verona, Italy before finally settling down in the artists' town [[Pietrasanta]] in Tuscany from 1971. Despite developing a style far removed from his Danish contemporaries, Haugen S\u00f8rensen has always been highly present in his native country in exhibitions as well as in the in the artistic debate.<ref name=\"AKN\" />\n\n==Career==\n\nAfter his debut at  [[Charlottenborg Palace|Charlottenborg]]'s spring exhibition in 1953, he rapidly gained a reputation as a sculptor who crafted works of the human body and of animals with intense expressiveness and realism. His scenes of butchery became central to his work.<ref name=Biography>{{Cite web|url=http://www.haugensorensen.com/biografiskoversigt|title=J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen - Biografisk oversigt|website=www.haugensorensen.com|language=da|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 1950s during a stay on the island of [[Bornholm]], he entered a more abstract phase, experimenting with tiled pipes and other ceramic products, although he maintained elements of the body and other recognizable phenomena. During the dramatic years of the [[Algerian War]], he settled in Paris creating figurative sculptures in bronze from 1959 to 1963. They depict scarred, torn organic forms reflecting a reality of cruelty, fear and sexuality. He traveled widely to Italy, Germany, Spain and Yugoslavia, developing a style which was far removed from Danish culture.<ref name=Helleland/> At the end of the 1960s, he often created compositions made up of several smaller sculptures, sometimes using materials such as plastic or textiles, occasionally borrowing elements from other sculptors.<ref name=Helleland/>\n\nAfter an interruption at the end of the 1960s when he turned to films, he returned to sculpture making use of marble, often combining different colours and finishes, as can be seen in his decorative work outside the School of Journalism in Aarhus. Other important works include the geometrical ''Huset der slikker solskin'' (The House which Licks Sunshine, 1980) for the Danish Institute in Rome, ''Dumhedens store flod'' (Stupidity's Great River, 1995) in [[Ribe]], and ''Sorg'' (Sorrow, 1990) for the French University in Istanbul. His later work often consists of large angular shapes with rough surfaces as his three sculptures for the University of Lund (1994) and his 7 meters tall ''Colossus'' at the [[Amager Strandpark|Amager Beach Park]] in Copenhagen.<ref name=\"Weilbach\" /><ref name=\"DSD\">[http://www.denstoredanske.dk/Kunst_og_kultur/Billedkunst/Kunstnere,_danske/J%C3%B8rgen_Haugen_S%C3%B8rensen?highlight=j%C3%B8rgen%20haugen%20s%C3%B8rensen \"J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen\"], ''Den Store Danske''. {{in lang|da}} Retrieved 4 June 2012.</ref> \n\nThroughout his career Haugen S\u00f8rensen has been rethinking how to work with sculpture, and according to him art is important precisely because it is the means through which society breathes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.haugensorensen.com/jrgenhaugenssrensenportrtfilm11|title=J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen - Portr\u00e6tfilm|website=www.haugensorensen.com|language=da|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> His oeuvre can thus largely be viewed as a commentary on basic conditions of human existence.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Helleland, Allis.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/180194528|title=J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen : a biography|date=2007|publisher=Statens Museum for Kunst|others=Bjerkhof, Sven., Statens museum for kunst (Denmark)|isbn=978-87-92023-03-2|location=[Copenhagen, Denmark]|oclc=180194528}}</ref>\n\n==Style==\n\nSince his debut in 1953 he has without any formal training or schooling shifted between materials and modes of expression within the sculptural sphere. His artistic language has evolved throughout his career, but the production has always kept an abstract core within its diversity.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Helleland, Allis.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/180194528|title=J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen : a biography|date=2007|publisher=Statens Museum for Kunst|others=Bjerkhof, Sven., Statens museum for kunst (Denmark)|isbn=978-87-92023-03-2|location=[Copenhagen, Denmark]|oclc=180194528}}</ref> He has primarily worked with sculptures even though he is also an accomplished [[draughtsman]].<ref name=Helleland/>\n\nHaugen S\u00f8rensen's works present his views of the human condition in his own, often brutal style. His reservations about the [[Royal Danish Academy of Fine Arts|Academy]]'s approach are evident in his oeuvre's glaring contrast to the generally theoretical approach of his contemporaries. Free of attachment to any given idiom, Haugen S\u00f8rensen channels his creative talents to depicting his own outlook on life, capturing the basic themes of life and death, love and suffering as the focal points of his sculpture, whether working with clay, plaster, fabric, terracotta, bronze, marble or granite.<ref name=\"AKN\">[http://artknowledgenews.com/200707293641/Jorgen_Haugen_Sorensen.html \"J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen at Statens Museum for Kunst\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921012902/http://artknowledgenews.com/200707293641/Jorgen_Haugen_Sorensen.html |date=2016-09-21 }}, ''ArtKnowledgeNews''. Retrieved 5 June 2012.</ref> \n\nJ\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensens inspiration stems from myriad places. From [[Francis Goya]]'s depictions of the Spanish peoples suffering during the [[Francisco Franco|Franco]] rule to [[Pablo Picasso|Pablo Picassos]] anti-war oil painting [[Guernica (Picasso)|''Guernica'']] from 1937 and his own memories of childhood visits in the slaughterhouses in the [[K\u00f8dbyen|Copenhagen Meat Packing District]] and readings of [[Kurt Vonnegut|Kurt Vonnegut's]] novel ''[[Slaughterhouse-Five|Slaughterhouse Five]]'' from 1969. Haugen S\u00f8rensen studied [[Gian Lorenzo Bernini|Gian Lorenzo Bernini's]] [[craftmanship]] and marble sculptures, the Mediterranean crafts traditions and he also took away ideas from his meeting with the [[Abstract expressionism|abstract expressionist art movement]] in Paris and [[COBRA (avant-garde movement)|CoBrA]] in the 1950s.<ref name=Helleland/>\n\n==Selected public works==\n\n* 2017 ''The Crowd'' Pietrasanta \u00a0\n* 2013 ''Justitio and the Witnesses'' the City Court Copenhagen \u00a0\n* 2010 ''Lump with suppor''t [[Danmarks Nationalbank|The Danish National Bank]] \u00a0\n* 2005 ''That\u2019s Why We Call Them Dogs'' [[National Museum of Denmark|Danish National Museum]] \u00a0\n* 1993 ''The House That Rains'', Skt. Hans Torv in Copenhagen \u00a0\n\n* 1988 ''Industrial Erection'' the [[Olympic Park, Seoul|Olympic Park in Seoul]], South Korea \n* 1983 ''The Angular One and the Smooth Ones Slide'' [[Assistens Cemetery (Copenhagen)|Assistants\u2019 Cemetery]] Copenhagen\n\nThe task of decorating the City Court in Copenhagen was originally assigned classical sculptor [[Bertel Thorvaldsen]] 200 years ago, but it was never completed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politiken.dk/magasinet/interview/art5506610/Kunstneren-og-digteren-har-gjort-det-Thorvaldsen-aldrig-n%C3%A5ede|title=Kunstneren og digteren har gjort det, Thorvaldsen aldrig n\u00e5ede|last=Winther|first=Tine Maria|date=2014-03-15|website=Politiken|language=da-DK|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==Selected solo exhibitions==\n\nA selection of Haugen S\u00f8rensen's exhibitions includes:<ref name=Biography/>\n\n* 2019 ''Time Meets Time'' [[Willumsens Museum|J. F. Willumsens Museum]] \n* 2017 ''The Crowd'' Piazza del Duomo Pietrasanta\n* 2014 ''Justitio og vidnerne'', [[Thorvaldsen Museum|Thorvaldsens Museum]], Copenhagen, Denmark\n* 2011 ''J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen in [[Cisternerne]]'', Cisternerne, Copenhagen, Denmark\n* 2011 I''n dialogue with Norbert Tadeusz'' [[Bornholm Art Museum]], Denmark\n* 2007 ''While we wait'' [[National Gallery of Denmark|Statens Museum for Kunst]] Copenhagen, Denmark\n* 2004 ''That\u2019s why they call them dogs'' Felleshuset der Nordischen Botschaften, Berlin, Germany\n* 2002  ''J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen'' [[Vigeland Museum|Vigeland Museet]], Oslo, Norway\n* 2000 ''Jeg Mener, jeg Ser'' Retrospektiv, KunstCentret Silkeborg Bad, Silkeborg og Sophienholm\n* 1999 ''Jeg mener, jeg ser'' [[Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek]] \n* 1993 ''Retrospektiv'' [[Yorkshire Sculpture Park]], England, \n* 1993 ''Silent Witness'' [[Museo de Arte Moderno]], Mexico City; Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Oaxaca; Museo de Xalapa, Mexico.\n* 1992 ''Retrospektiv Charlottenborg with Carl Henning Petersen'' [[Kunsthal Charlottenborg]] Copenhagen, Denmark\n* 1991 ''The Cyplos'' with [[Christian Lemmerz]], [[Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek]], Copenhagen, Denmark\n* 1983 [[San Jose Museum of Art|San Jos\u00e9 Museum of Art]] California, US\n* 1982 [[Charles Cowles (art dealer)|Charles Cowles Gallery]] New York, US\n* 1980 ''J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen'' at [[Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek|Ny Carlsberg Glyptoteket]], Copenhagen Denmark\n* 1976 ''J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen'', [[Henie Onstad Kunstsenter|Sonja Henies og Niels Onstads Stiftelser]], H\u00f8vikodden, Norway\n* 1975 [[Louisiana Museum of Modern Art]], m. Giovanni Meloni, Humleb\u00e6k, Denmark\n* 1964 ''Fire Billedhuggere'' [[Louisiana Museum of Modern Art]], Humleb\u00e6k, Denmark\n* 1963 ''Untitled'' Galerie Ariel, Paris, France\n* 1961 Galleria del Naviglio, Milano, Italy\n* 1960 Galerie B\u00f8rge Birch, Copenhagen, Denmark\n\n==Selected group exhibitions==\n\n* 2020 ''Gr\u00f8nningen'' [[Den Frie Udstilling|Den Frie Udstillingsbygning]], Copenhagen, DK \n* 1980 [[XI International Sculpture Conference]] Washington DC, US\n* 1979 15 Biennale [[Middelheim Open Air Sculpture Museum|Middelheim Sculpture Park]], Antwerpen, Belgium\n* 1966 Jeune Sculpture [[Mus\u00e9e Rodin]], 1966, 1969, Paris, France\n* 1961 The Pittsburgh International Exhibition of Contemporary Painting and Sculpture Museum of Art, [[Carnegie Museums of Pittsburgh|Carnegie Institute]], Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, US\n* 1959 Youth Biennial, Paris 1959 and 1963, Wins the jury award in 1963 and 1965\n* 1958 [[Venice Biennale|Biennale di Venezia]], Italy\n\n==Collections ==\n[[Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek]], [[National Gallery of Denmark]], [[Louisiana Museum of Modern Art|Louisiana, Museum of Modern Art]], [[Carnegie Institute]], [[National Gallery (Norway)|Nasjonalgalleriet]], [[Henie Onstad Kunstsenter]] [[Museum of Modern Art|MoMA]] Museum of Modern Art, [[Yorkshire Sculpture Park]], Portofino Sculpture Park, [[KUNSTEN Museum of Modern Art Aalborg|Kunsten Museum of Modern Art Aalborg]], [[Herning Museum of Contemporary Art|HEART]]. \n\nIn 2014 Haugen S\u00f8rensen donated a significant part of his private collection to [[Bornholm Art Museum|Bornholms Kunstmuseum]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bornholms-kunstmuseum.dk/oplev/tidligere-udstillinger/udstillinger-2014/gaven-joergen-haugen-soerensen.aspx|title=GAVEN - J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen - Bornholms Kunstmuseum|website=www.bornholms-kunstmuseum.dk|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>. \n\n==Awards and recognitions==\n\n* Represented Denmark at [[Venice Biennale|La Biennale di Venezia]] in 1958\n* The [[Eckersberg Medal]] in 1969\n* The [[Thorvaldsen Medal]] in 1979\n* [[Danish Arts Foundation|Statens Kunstfonds]] livsvarige h\u00e6dersydelse in 1984.<ref name=\"DSD\" />\n\n== Art market and fairs ==\nHaugen S\u00f8rensen is represented by Copenhagen based Hans Alf Gallery as well as by UK based Messums Wiltshire<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hansalf.com/|title=Home|website=www.hansalf.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://messumswiltshire.com/|title=Messums Wiltshire - Gallery and Arts Centre - Tisbury, Wiltshire|website=Messums Wiltshire|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>. He has exhibited his work at international art fairs such as Art Herning, [[SCOPE Art Show|Scope Basel]] and [[SCOPE Art Show|Scope New York]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Haugen S\u00f8rensen, J\u00f8rgen: ''Souvenir: J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen'', 1993, Copenhagen, Charlottenborg. {{ISBN|8788944263}}.\n\n{{commons category|J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haugen Sorensen, Jorgen}}\n[[Category:Danish sculptors]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Artists from Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Eckersberg Medal]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Thorvaldsen Medal]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen.tif|alt=|thumb|J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen, 2007]]\n'''J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen''' (born 3 October 1934, Copenhagen) is one of Denmark's most eminent sculptors. He had his artistic debut at the acclaimed and prestigious [https://kunsthalcharlottenborg.dk/da/udstillinger/charlottenborg-foraarsudstilling-2020/ Spring Exhibition] (''For\u00e5rsudstillingen'') at [[Kunsthal Charlottenborg]], Copenhagen in 1953. Haugen S\u00f8rensen is a member of the artistic union [https://decembristerne.info Decembristerne] and the artist collective [[Gr\u00f8nningen]], as well as Veks\u00f8lund in Denmark. \n\nThe post-war and contemporary sculptor has been hailed{{by whom|date=April 2020}} as the greatest Danish sculptor since [[Bertel Thorvaldsen]]. He has received several important distinctions for his works through the years, such as the [[Eckersberg Medal|Eckerberg Medal]] in 1969{{cn|date=April 2020}} and the [[Thorvaldsen Medal]] in 1979.{{cn|date=April 2020}} In 1958 he was selected to represent Denmark at the [[Venice Biennale|Biennale di Venezia]].<ref name=Helleland>{{Cite book|last=Helleland|first=Allis|title=J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen : a biography|date=2007|publisher=Statens Museum for Kunst|others=Bjerkhof, Sven., Statens museum for kunst (Denmark)|isbn=978-87-92023-03-2|location=[Copenhagen, Denmark]|oclc=180194528}}</ref> Haugen S\u00f8rensen's sculptures are placed all around the world.<ref name=Helleland/>\n\n==Early life==\nAs a child, together with his brother [[Arne Haugen S\u00f8rensen|Arne]], Haugen S\u00f8rensen began to draw and later to model. When he was 15, he trained as a plasterer and potter and then attended the [[Danmarks Designskole|Design School]] in Copenhagen.  As a sculptor, however, he was self-taught.<ref name=Weilbach>[https://www.kulturarv.dk/kid/VisWeilbach.do?kunstnerId=1056&wsektion=alle Pia Kristine M\u00fcnster, \"J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen\"], ''Kunstindeks Danmark & Weilbachs Kunstnerleksikon''. {{in lang|da}} Retrieved 4 June 2012.</ref>\n\nJ\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen has spent most of his life abroad, living in a voluntary exile in Southern Europe. The 1960s he spent in Paris, France and Verona, Italy before finally settling down in the artists' town [[Pietrasanta]] in Tuscany from 1971. Despite developing a style far removed from his Danish contemporaries, Haugen S\u00f8rensen has always been highly present in his native country in exhibitions as well as in the in the artistic debate.<ref name=\"AKN\" />\n\n==Career==\n\nAfter his debut at  [[Charlottenborg Palace|Charlottenborg]]'s spring exhibition in 1953, he rapidly gained a reputation as a sculptor who crafted works of the human body and of animals with intense expressiveness and realism. His scenes of butchery became central to his work.<ref name=Biography>{{Cite web|url=http://www.haugensorensen.com/biografiskoversigt|title=J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen - Biografisk oversigt|website=www.haugensorensen.com|language=da|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 1950s during a stay on the island of [[Bornholm]], he entered a more abstract phase, experimenting with tiled pipes and other ceramic products, although he maintained elements of the body and other recognizable phenomena. During the dramatic years of the [[Algerian War]], he settled in Paris creating figurative sculptures in bronze from 1959 to 1963. They depict scarred, torn organic forms reflecting a reality of cruelty, fear and sexuality. He traveled widely to Italy, Germany, Spain and Yugoslavia, developing a style which was far removed from Danish culture.<ref name=Helleland/> At the end of the 1960s, he often created compositions made up of several smaller sculptures, sometimes using materials such as plastic or textiles, occasionally borrowing elements from other sculptors.<ref name=Helleland/>\n\nAfter an interruption at the end of the 1960s when he turned to films, he returned to sculpture making use of marble, often combining different colours and finishes, as can be seen in his decorative work outside the School of Journalism in Aarhus. Other important works include the geometrical ''Huset der slikker solskin'' (The House which Licks Sunshine, 1980) for the Danish Institute in Rome, ''Dumhedens store flod'' (Stupidity's Great River, 1995) in [[Ribe]], and ''Sorg'' (Sorrow, 1990) for the French University in Istanbul. His later work often consists of large angular shapes with rough surfaces as his three sculptures for the University of Lund (1994) and his 7 meters tall ''Colossus'' at the [[Amager Strandpark|Amager Beach Park]] in Copenhagen.<ref name=\"Weilbach\" /><ref name=\"DSD\">[http://www.denstoredanske.dk/Kunst_og_kultur/Billedkunst/Kunstnere,_danske/J%C3%B8rgen_Haugen_S%C3%B8rensen?highlight=j%C3%B8rgen%20haugen%20s%C3%B8rensen \"J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen\"], ''Den Store Danske''. {{in lang|da}} Retrieved 4 June 2012.</ref> \n\nThroughout his career Haugen S\u00f8rensen has been rethinking how to work with sculpture, and according to him art is important precisely because it is the means through which society breathes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.haugensorensen.com/jrgenhaugenssrensenportrtfilm11|title=J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen - Portr\u00e6tfilm|website=www.haugensorensen.com|language=da|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> His oeuvre can thus largely be viewed as a commentary on basic conditions of human existence.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Style==\n\nSince his debut in 1953 he has without any formal training or schooling shifted between materials and modes of expression within the sculptural sphere. His artistic language has evolved throughout his career, but the production has always kept an abstract core within its diversity.{{cn|date=April 2020}} He has primarily worked with sculptures even though he is also an accomplished [[draughtsman]].<ref name=Helleland/>\n\nHaugen S\u00f8rensen's works present his views of the human condition in his own, often brutal style. His reservations about the [[Royal Danish Academy of Fine Arts|Academy]]'s approach are evident in his oeuvre's glaring contrast to the generally theoretical approach of his contemporaries. Free of attachment to any given idiom, Haugen S\u00f8rensen channels his creative talents to depicting his own outlook on life, capturing the basic themes of life and death, love and suffering as the focal points of his sculpture, whether working with clay, plaster, fabric, terracotta, bronze, marble or granite.<ref name=\"AKN\">[http://artknowledgenews.com/200707293641/Jorgen_Haugen_Sorensen.html \"J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen at Statens Museum for Kunst\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921012902/http://artknowledgenews.com/200707293641/Jorgen_Haugen_Sorensen.html |date=2016-09-21 }}, ''ArtKnowledgeNews''. Retrieved 5 June 2012.</ref> \n\nJ\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensens inspiration stems from myriad places. From [[Francis Goya]]'s depictions of the Spanish peoples suffering during the [[Francisco Franco|Franco]] rule to [[Pablo Picasso|Pablo Picassos]] anti-war oil painting [[Guernica (Picasso)|''Guernica'']] from 1937 and his own memories of childhood visits in the slaughterhouses in the [[K\u00f8dbyen|Copenhagen Meat Packing District]] and readings of [[Kurt Vonnegut|Kurt Vonnegut's]] novel ''[[Slaughterhouse-Five|Slaughterhouse Five]]'' from 1969. Haugen S\u00f8rensen studied [[Gian Lorenzo Bernini|Gian Lorenzo Bernini's]] [[craftmanship]] and marble sculptures, the Mediterranean crafts traditions and he also took away ideas from his meeting with the [[Abstract expressionism|abstract expressionist art movement]] in Paris and [[COBRA (avant-garde movement)|CoBrA]] in the 1950s.<ref name=Helleland/>\n\n==Selected public works==\n\n* 2017 ''The Crowd'' Pietrasanta \u00a0\n* 2013 ''Justitio and the Witnesses'' the City Court Copenhagen \u00a0\n* 2010 ''Lump with suppor''t [[Danmarks Nationalbank|The Danish National Bank]] \u00a0\n* 2005 ''That\u2019s Why We Call Them Dogs'' [[National Museum of Denmark|Danish National Museum]] \u00a0\n* 1993 ''The House That Rains'', Skt. Hans Torv in Copenhagen \u00a0\n\n* 1988 ''Industrial Erection'' the [[Olympic Park, Seoul|Olympic Park in Seoul]], South Korea \n* 1983 ''The Angular One and the Smooth Ones Slide'' [[Assistens Cemetery (Copenhagen)|Assistants\u2019 Cemetery]] Copenhagen\n\nThe task of decorating the City Court in Copenhagen was originally assigned classical sculptor [[Bertel Thorvaldsen]] 200 years ago, but it was never completed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politiken.dk/magasinet/interview/art5506610/Kunstneren-og-digteren-har-gjort-det-Thorvaldsen-aldrig-n%C3%A5ede|title=Kunstneren og digteren har gjort det, Thorvaldsen aldrig n\u00e5ede|last=Winther|first=Tine Maria|date=2014-03-15|website=Politiken|language=da-DK|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==Selected solo exhibitions==\n\nA selection of Haugen S\u00f8rensen's exhibitions includes:<ref name=Biography/>\n\n* 2019 ''Time Meets Time'' [[Willumsens Museum|J. F. Willumsens Museum]] \n* 2017 ''The Crowd'' Piazza del Duomo Pietrasanta\n* 2014 ''Justitio og vidnerne'', [[Thorvaldsen Museum|Thorvaldsens Museum]], Copenhagen, Denmark\n* 2011 ''J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen in [[Cisternerne]]'', Cisternerne, Copenhagen, Denmark\n* 2011 I''n dialogue with Norbert Tadeusz'' [[Bornholm Art Museum]], Denmark\n* 2007 ''While we wait'' [[National Gallery of Denmark|Statens Museum for Kunst]] Copenhagen, Denmark\n* 2004 ''That\u2019s why they call them dogs'' Felleshuset der Nordischen Botschaften, Berlin, Germany\n* 2002  ''J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen'' [[Vigeland Museum|Vigeland Museet]], Oslo, Norway\n* 2000 ''Jeg Mener, jeg Ser'' Retrospektiv, KunstCentret Silkeborg Bad, Silkeborg og Sophienholm\n* 1999 ''Jeg mener, jeg ser'' [[Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek]] \n* 1993 ''Retrospektiv'' [[Yorkshire Sculpture Park]], England, \n* 1993 ''Silent Witness'' [[Museo de Arte Moderno]], Mexico City; Museo de Arte Contempor\u00e1neo de Oaxaca; Museo de Xalapa, Mexico.\n* 1992 ''Retrospektiv Charlottenborg with Carl Henning Petersen'' [[Kunsthal Charlottenborg]] Copenhagen, Denmark\n* 1991 ''The Cyplos'' with [[Christian Lemmerz]], [[Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek]], Copenhagen, Denmark\n* 1983 [[San Jose Museum of Art|San Jos\u00e9 Museum of Art]] California, US\n* 1982 [[Charles Cowles (art dealer)|Charles Cowles Gallery]] New York, US\n* 1980 ''J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen'' at [[Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek|Ny Carlsberg Glyptoteket]], Copenhagen Denmark\n* 1976 ''J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen'', [[Henie Onstad Kunstsenter|Sonja Henies og Niels Onstads Stiftelser]], H\u00f8vikodden, Norway\n* 1975 [[Louisiana Museum of Modern Art]], m. Giovanni Meloni, Humleb\u00e6k, Denmark\n* 1964 ''Fire Billedhuggere'' [[Louisiana Museum of Modern Art]], Humleb\u00e6k, Denmark\n* 1963 ''Untitled'' Galerie Ariel, Paris, France\n* 1961 Galleria del Naviglio, Milano, Italy\n* 1960 Galerie B\u00f8rge Birch, Copenhagen, Denmark\n\n==Selected group exhibitions==\n\n* 2020 ''Gr\u00f8nningen'' [[Den Frie Udstilling|Den Frie Udstillingsbygning]], Copenhagen, DK \n* 1980 [[XI International Sculpture Conference]] Washington DC, US\n* 1979 15 Biennale [[Middelheim Open Air Sculpture Museum|Middelheim Sculpture Park]], Antwerpen, Belgium\n* 1966 Jeune Sculpture [[Mus\u00e9e Rodin]], 1966, 1969, Paris, France\n* 1961 The Pittsburgh International Exhibition of Contemporary Painting and Sculpture Museum of Art, [[Carnegie Museums of Pittsburgh|Carnegie Institute]], Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, US\n* 1959 Youth Biennial, Paris 1959 and 1963, Wins the jury award in 1963 and 1965\n* 1958 [[Venice Biennale|Biennale di Venezia]], Italy\n\n==Collections ==\n[[Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek]], [[National Gallery of Denmark]], [[Louisiana Museum of Modern Art|Louisiana, Museum of Modern Art]], [[Carnegie Institute]], [[National Gallery (Norway)|Nasjonalgalleriet]], [[Henie Onstad Kunstsenter]] [[Museum of Modern Art|MoMA]] Museum of Modern Art, [[Yorkshire Sculpture Park]], Portofino Sculpture Park, [[KUNSTEN Museum of Modern Art Aalborg|Kunsten Museum of Modern Art Aalborg]], [[Herning Museum of Contemporary Art|HEART]]. \n\nIn 2014 Haugen S\u00f8rensen donated a significant part of his private collection to [[Bornholm Art Museum|Bornholms Kunstmuseum]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bornholms-kunstmuseum.dk/oplev/tidligere-udstillinger/udstillinger-2014/gaven-joergen-haugen-soerensen.aspx|title=GAVEN - J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen - Bornholms Kunstmuseum|website=www.bornholms-kunstmuseum.dk|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>. \n\n==Awards and recognitions==\n\n* Represented Denmark at [[Venice Biennale|La Biennale di Venezia]] in 1958\n* The [[Eckersberg Medal]] in 1969\n* The [[Thorvaldsen Medal]] in 1979\n* [[Danish Arts Foundation|Statens Kunstfonds]] livsvarige h\u00e6dersydelse in 1984.<ref name=\"DSD\" />\n\n== Art market and fairs ==\nHaugen S\u00f8rensen  has exhibited his work at international art fairs such as Art Herning, [[SCOPE Art Show|Scope Basel]] and [[SCOPE Art Show|Scope New York]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Haugen S\u00f8rensen, J\u00f8rgen: ''Souvenir: J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen'', 1993, Copenhagen, Charlottenborg. {{ISBN|8788944263}}.\n\n{{commons category|J\u00f8rgen Haugen S\u00f8rensen}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haugen Sorensen, Jorgen}}\n[[Category:Danish sculptors]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Artists from Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Eckersberg Medal]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Thorvaldsen Medal]]\n", "name_user": "LouiseHenriksen13052017", "label": "safe", "comment": "I added citations.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J%C3%B8rgen_Haugen_S%C3%B8rensen"}
{"title_page": "Leroy Burrell", "text_new": "{{short description|American former track and field athlete|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Leroy Burrell\n| image          =\n| caption        = Burrell at the [[2019 Parapan American Games]]\n| fullname       = Leroy Russel Burrell\n| nationality    = [[Americans|American]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1967|02|21|mf=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| residence      = [[Houston]], [[Texas]], U.S.\n| height         = 6 ft 0 in\n| weight         = 180 lb\n| sport          = [[Track and field]]\n| event          = [[Sprint (running)|Sprints]] and [[long jump]]\n| collegeteam    = [[Houston Cougars]] (1985-1990)\n| club           = [[Santa Monica Track Club]]\n| coach          = [[Tom Tellez]]<ref name=1991100mWR/>\n| retired        = 1998<ref>{{cite web |url=https://uhcougars.com/coaches.aspx?rc=462&path=track |title=Leroy Burrell |website=uhcougars.com |publisher=[[Houston Cougars]] |accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref>\n| pb             = {{Unbulleted list\n|'''60&nbsp;m''': 6.48&nbsp;s (1991)\n|'''100&nbsp;m''': 9.86&nbsp;s (1994)\n|'''200&nbsp;m''': 20.12&nbsp;s (1992)\n|'''Long jump''': 8.37&nbsp;m (1989)}}\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport| Men\u2019s [[Sport of athletics|athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry| the {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition| [[Athletics at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[Athletics at the 1992 Summer Olympics|1992 Barcelona]] | [[Athletics at the 1992 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metres relay|4\u00d7100&nbsp;m relay]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition| [[IAAF World Championships in Athletics|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[1991 World Championships in Athletics|1991 Tokyo]] | [[1991 World Championships in Athletics - Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metres relay|4\u00d7100&nbsp;m relay]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[1993 World Championships in Athletics|1993 Stuttgart]] | [[1993 World Championships in Athletics - Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metres relay|4\u00d7100&nbsp;m relay]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| 1991 Tokyo | [[1991 World Championships in Athletics - Men's 100 metres|100&nbsp;m]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition| [[Athletics at the Goodwill Games|Goodwill Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[Athletics at the 1990 Goodwill Games|1990 Seattle]] | [[Athletics at the 1990 Goodwill Games \u2013 Results#100 meters|100&nbsp;m]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[Athletics at the 1994 Goodwill Games|1994 St. Petersburg]] | [[Athletics at the 1994 Goodwill Games \u2013 Results#100 meters|100&nbsp;m]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition| [[IAAF World Cup|World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[1989 IAAF World Cup|1989 Barcelona]] | [[1989 IAAF World Cup \u2013 Results#Men|100&nbsp;m]]}}\n}}\n'''Leroy Russel Burrell''' (born February 21, 1967) is an [[United States|American]] former [[track and field]] athlete, who twice set the [[men's 100 metres world record progression|world record]] for the [[100 metres|100&nbsp;m]] [[Sprint (running)|sprint]].\n\n==Early life==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=April 2019}}\nBurrell grew up in [[Lansdowne, Pennsylvania]], and attended [[Penn Wood High School]], where he single-handedly won the state championship by winning the 100&nbsp;m, [[200 metres|200&nbsp;m]], [[long jump]], and [[triple jump]]. Suffering from poor eyesight accentuated by a childhood eye injury, he was poor at other sports, but excelled on the track from an early age.\n\n==Professional career==\nBurrell was plagued by injuries and bad luck throughout his career, particularly around major championships. He won [[Gold medal|gold]] in the 100&nbsp;m ahead of Carl Lewis at the 1990 [[Goodwill Games]] in [[Seattle]]. He won the [[Silver medal|silver]] in the 100&nbsp;m behind Lewis at the [[1991 World Championships in Athletics|1991 World Championships]]. At the [[1992 Summer Olympics]] in [[Barcelona]], Burrell false-started in the 100&nbsp;m final. When the race finally restarted, his reaction off the line was slow, and he finished fifth. He did manage to win a [[relay race|relay]] gold as part of the U.S. 4 \u00d7 100 m team.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nOn May 19, 1990, Burrell ran a wind-assisted 200&nbsp;m at [[College Station, Texas|College Station]], Texas, in a time of 19.61 seconds. The wind speed was +4.0 m per second. This was the fastest time for the 200&nbsp;m for over six years until the 1996 Olympic final in Atlanta, where [[Michael Johnson (sprinter)|Michael Johnson]] ran 19.32 seconds.\n\nHe first set the world record in June 1991 with a time of 9.90&nbsp;seconds. This was broken that September by [[Carl Lewis]] who ran 9.86&nbsp;sec at the [[1991 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's 100 metres|1991 World Track and Field Championships]] where Burrell finished second in a new personal best time of 9.88&nbsp;sec. In July 1994, Burrell set the world record for the second time when he ran 9.85&nbsp;sec (a record that stood until the [[1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Olympics]] when [[Donovan Bailey]] ran 9.84&nbsp;sec).{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nSince his [[retirement]] in 1998, Burrell has replaced his old college mentor, [[Tom Tellez]], as coach of the University of Houston's track team. Burrell has led UH to 14 men's [[Conference USA]] titles (nine indoor, five outdoor) and nine women's titles (four indoor, five outdoor). He was inducted into the Texas Track and Field Coaches Hall of Fame in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ttfca2.wixsite.com/txtfhalloffame/inductees |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-01-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116170038/http://ttfca2.wixsite.com/txtfhalloffame/inductees |archive-date=2017-01-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBurrell married [[Michelle Finn-Burrell|Michelle Finn]], also a sprinter, in 1994, and they have three sons: Cameron, a sprinter for the [[Houston Cougars]],<ref>{{cite web |title=In His Parents\u2019 Very Fast Footsteps |author=Jer\u00e9 Longman |date=May 23, 2013 |website=nytimes.com |publisher=[[New York Times]] |accessdate=April 28, 2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/23/sports/cameron-burrell-is-following-in-very-fast-footsteps.html}}</ref> Joshua, and Jaden. On June 7, 2017, Cameron joined his father in the [[10-second barrier|sub-10 second club]]. Burrell's younger sister [[Dawn Burrell|Dawn]] also competed in track and field at the highest level and she was a [[2001 IAAF World Indoor Championships \u2013 Women's long jump|world indoor champion]] in the long jump.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n==Statistics==\nInformation from [[IAAF]] profile unless otherwise noted.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.iaaf.org/athletes/united-states/leroy-burrell-392 |title=Leroy BURRELL {{!}} Profile |website=iaaf.org |publisher=[[IAAF]] |accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===World records===\nIncludes former all-conditions world best in the 200 meters. All world records are former as of May 24, 2014.\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n! Event !! Time (s) !! Competition !! Venue !! Date !! Notes\n|-\n| [[60&nbsp;m]] || 6.48 || Madrid indoor meet || [[Madrid, Spain]] || February 13, 1991 || {{refn|group=note|name=60mWR}} <ref name=60mWR/><ref name=60mWR1.2/>\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[100&nbsp;m]] || 9.90 || [[1991 USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships|U.S. Championships]] || [[Downing Stadium|New York, New York]], U.S. || June 14, 1991 || +1.8&nbsp;m/s wind {{refn|group=note|name=100mWR|American [[Carl Lewis]] broke Leroy Burrell's 9.90&nbsp;s world record in the 100&nbsp;m two months later at the [[1991 World Championships in Athletics|1991 World Championships]] with a time of 9.86&nbsp;s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/vault/1991/09/02/124837/the-great-race-carl-lewis-shattered-the-world-record-in-the-best-100-meter-dash-ever-run |title=THE GREAT RACE |author=Kenny Moore |website=si.com |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=September 2, 1991 |accessdate=April 28, 2019}}</ref>}} <ref name=1991100mWR>{{ci