{"title_page": "Tom Wright (Australian actor)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name           = Thomas M. Wright\n| image          = ThomasMwright.jpg\n| caption        = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1983|6|22}}\n| birth_place    = [[Melbourne]], Australia\n| death_date     = \n| birth_name     = Thomas Michael Wright\n| years_active   = 1998\u2013present\n| other_names    = Thomas M. Wright\n| occupation     = Actor, producer, writer, director, theatre designer\n| spouse         =\n}}\n'''Thomas Michael Wright''' (born 22 June 1983) is an Australian actor, writer, director and producer. He is the director of the feature film ''Acute Misfortune'' and the co-founder and director of theatre company Black Lung. As an actor he came to attention in [[Jane Campion]]'s series ''[[Top of the Lake]]'', for which he was nominated for Best Supporting Actor at the US Critics Choice Awards.<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/big-bang-theory-unbeatable-as-aussies-sink-at-tv-critics-awards-20130612-2o32f.html</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWright was born June 22, 1983 in [[Melbourne]], the eldest of three children.{{cn|date=February 2019}}\n\n==Career==\nWright is the director, co-writer and producer of the feature film ''Acute Misfortune'', based on Erik Jensen's biography of Australian artist [[Adam Cullen]].<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/books/erik-jensens-biography-of-flawed-artist-adam-cullen-wins-sydney-literary-award-20151124-gl66v0.html</ref> The film debuted at the [[Melbourne International Film Festival]], where it was the winner of ''The Age'' Critic's Award for Best Australian Feature Film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://miff.com.au/program/film/acute-misfortune|title=Acute Misfortune|website=MIFF|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-08-24}}</ref>.  The film received a five star review in The Guardian<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/aug/04/acute-misfortune-first-look-review-adam-cullen-biopic-is-an-enthralling-complex-triumph</ref> and was named one of the best films of 2018 in The Monthly Awards<ref>https://www.themonthly.com.au/issue/2018/october/1538316000/monthly-awards-2018/2018</ref> and by Screen Daily.<ref>https://www.screendaily.com/features/films-of-the-year-2018-sarah-ward/5135405.article</ref> [[Hollywood Reporter|The Hollywood Reporter]] called Acute Misfortune 'one of the year's most striking and accomplished directorial debuts'<ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/acute-misfortune-1135575</ref>. The score, by [[Evelyn Morris|Evelyn Ida Morris]], was nominated for best soundtrack at the 2018 [[ARIA awards|ARIA Awards]]<ref>https://www.ariaawards.com.au/news/2018/2018-aria-award-nominees-announced</ref> and the film was nominated for the 2019 AACTA Award for Best Independent Film<ref>https://www.aacta.org/aacta-awards/winners-and-nominees/</ref>. ''Acute Misfortune'' was named one of The Guardian's [https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/dec/10/from-animal-kingdom-to-the-babadook-the-best-australian-films-of-the-decade 10 Best Australian Films of the decade 2010-2020] and [https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/dec/16/from-the-final-quarter-to-judy-punch-the-best-australian-films-of-2019 the best Australian film of 2019]<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/dec/16/from-the-final-quarter-to-judy-punch-the-best-australian-films-of-2019</ref>.\n\nAs an actor, Wright came to attention in the Sundance / BBC series ''Top of the Lake'', for which he was nominated for Best Supporting Actor at the US Critics' Choice Awards.<ref name=smh2013>{{cite web | title=Big Bang Theory unbeatable as Aussies sink at TV Critics' awards | website=The Sydney Morning Herald | date=12 June 2013 | url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/big-bang-theory-unbeatable-as-aussies-sink-at-tv-critics-awards-20130612-2o32f.html | access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=variety2013>{{cite web | title=Critics\u2019 Choice TV Awards Announced \u2013 Variety | website=Variety | url=https://variety.com/2013/tv/awards/bcta-1200486013/ | access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> Regarding his casting as Johnno Mitcham in the series, director Jane Campion compared him to a young Daniel Day Lewis.<ref>https://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/actor-tom-wright-is-at-the-top-of-his-game-with-jane-campion-television-project/news-story/0e3d8f493da8ec1c09ced262b758f396}}</ref> In 2018 he featured in Warwick Thornton's ''Sweet Country'', which received the Venice Film Festival Special Jury Prize, the AACTA Award for Best Film and The Toronto Film Festival Platform Prize<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/sweet-country-dominates-aacta-awards-with-a-surprise-best-actor-win-20181204-p50k25.html</ref>.\n\nWright featured in the film ''[[The Man with the Iron Heart (film)|The Man With The Iron Heart]]'', an adaptation of Laurent Binet's [[HHhH|Prix De Goncourt winning novel]], with Jack O\u2019Connell, Stephen Graham and Jason Clarke.<ref>https://cineuropa.org/film/330810/</ref> He also filmed the Sony / WGN America Series ''Outsiders'' in the lead role of Sheriff Wade Houghton for producers Peter Tolan and Paul Giamatti. His performance was cited as the standout of the series by ''Hollywood Reporter''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/reviews/outsiders-review-wgn-america-david-morse-1201677147/|title=TV Review: \u2018Outsiders\u2019|last=Lowry|first=Brian|website=Variety|language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> and ''Variety''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/outsiders-tv-review-859145|title='Outsiders': TV Review|website=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIn 2015, Wright filmed the Universal / Working Title feature ''[[Everest (2015 film)|Everest]]'', based on the 1996 \u2018Into Thin Air\u2019 tragedy. Years before the film, Wright walked for a month in the Himalayas on his own, without a porter or guide, crossing the highest mountain pass in the world. He walked for 30 days and lost sixteen kilograms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bbc.co.uk/|title=BBC - Home|website=bbc.co.uk|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> He appeared as cult-figure Steven Linder in the US adaptation of ''[[The Bridge (2013 TV series)|The Bridge]]''. Executive Producer Elwood Reid said of Wright\u2019s audition for the series \u2018it was the best audition I have ever seen. He walked in and the temperature of the room changed.\u2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/entertainment/a/17835120/aussie-actor-wright-repulses-us-producer/|title=Aussie actor Wright repulses US producer|website=au.news.yahoo.com|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> He also played the murdered journalist Brian Peters in ''[[Balibo (film)|Balibo]]'' (2009), and Thomas Bodenham in [[Van Diemen's Land (film)|Van Diemen's Land]].<ref>http://theatrenotes.blogspot.com/2009/03/review-van-diemans-land.html</ref>\n\nWright has played lead roles for the [[Malthouse Theatre]], Melbourne Theatre Company and Sydney Theatre Company, including the title role Baal in the controversial production commissioned by Artistic Directors Cate Blanchett and Andrew Upton and directed by Simon Stone.<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/theatre/baal-20110512-1ekm1.html</ref>\n\nWright created Black Lung in 2006, with fellow writer and director [[William_Light#Stage|Thomas Henning]]. Black Lung were acclaimed{{by whom?|date=March 2019}} for their anarchic process and performance style.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.realtimearts.net/article/74/8185|title=RealTime Arts - Magazine -  issue 74 - The sweet breath of The Black Lung|website=www.realtimearts.net|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> and hailed as one of the most influential theatre companies of the decade.<ref>https://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/now-for-something-different/news-story/fdd1f8e39838afe6bccb9d26d7152d9e</ref> Under the Black Lung banner, Wright created productions with [[Adelaide Festival]] and [[Darwin Festival]], [[Belvoir (theatre company)|Belvoir]], Malthouse Theatre, and [[Queensland Theatre Company|Queensland Theatre Co.]] and [[Brisbane Festival]].{{cn|date=March 2019}}\n\nWright was the director, co-writer and production designer of ''Doku Rai,'' a production created over four and a half years, with a three-month rehearsal process on the remote island of Atauro, East Timor. ''Doku Rai'' came about after Wright formed a close relationship with Michael Stone, then Chief Military Advisor to the President of Timor, [[Jos\u00e9 Ramos-Horta]]. Stone facilitated Wright flying in and out of the country over a number of years. ''Doku Rai'' was created with a group of independent Timorese artists, a number of them former resistance fighters. The film sequences in ''Doku Rai'' were co-directed by Wright with director Amiel Courtin-Wilson.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/movies/from-the-wild-zone-20120810-23z2m.html|title=From the wild zone {{!}} Doku Rai at Arts House {{!}} Amiel Courtin-Wilson|last=Power|first=Liza|date=2012-08-11|newspaper=The Age|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/booksandarts/actor-director-thomas-m-wright-and-doku-rai/4964826|title=Actor and director Thomas M Wright and 'Doku Rai|website=Radio National|language=en-AU|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Wright was the subject of an Archibald Prize finalist portrait by Marcus Wills, 'Antagonist / Protagonist (Thomas M. Wight)'.<ref>https://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/prizes/archibald/2017/29858/</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n|2000 || [[Stepsister from Planet Weird]] || Cutter Colburne\n|-\n| 2001 || ''[[Zenon: The Zequel]]'' || Orion\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[The King (2007 film)|The King]]'' || Alfie\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Van Diemen's Land (film)|Van Diemen's Land]]'' || Thomas Bodenham\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Balibo (film)|Balibo]]'' || Brian Peters\n|-\n| 2010 || ''Torn'' || Tim Strauss\n|-\n| 2015 || [[Everest (2015 film)|''Everest'']] || [[Michael Groom (climber)|Michael Groom]]\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[The Man with the Iron Heart (film)|The Man with the Iron Heart]]'' || [[Josef Valcik]]\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Sweet Country (2017 film)|Sweet Country]]'' || Mick Kennedy\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Top of the Lake]]'' || Johnno Mitcham\n|-\n| 2013\u20132015 || ''[[The Bridge (2013 TV series)|The Bridge]]'' || Steven Linder\n|-\n| 2016\u20132017 || ''[[Outsiders (TV series)|Outsiders]]'' || Sheriff Wade Houghton\n|}\n\n===Stage===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2004 || ''51 Ashworth St.'' || The Boy || Co-writer, co-director, designer\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Hamlet]]'' || Laertes || Beggars Theatre\n|-\n| 2007 || ''The Glass Soldier'' || Jonas Fink ||  Melbourne Theatre Company\n|-\n| 2007 || ''Pimms'' || Dying Man || Writer, co-director<br />The Black Lung Theatre\n|-\n| 2008 || ''Love Song'' || Beane || Melbourne Theatre Company\n|-\n| 2008 || ''Avast I'' || The Older Brother || Malthouse Theatre\n|-\n| 2008 || ''Avast II'' || Jack Lemmon || Co-director, designer<br />Malthouse Theatre\n|-\n| 2009 || ''Glasson'' || God || The Black Lung Theatre\n|-\n| 2010 || ''Furious Mattress'' || The Exorcist || Malthouse Theatre\n|-\n| 2011 || ''Baal'' || Baal || Sydney Theatre Company\n|-\n| 2011 || ''And They Called Him Mr. Glamour'' || || Director, designer<br />Belvoir St. Theatre\n|-\n| 2011 || ''I Feel Awful'' || || Writer, director, designer<br />Brisbane Festival\n|-\n| 2013 || ''Doku Rai'' || || Co-writer, director, designer<br />The Black Lung Theatre\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{iMDb name|0942876}}\n* [http://www.theblacklung.com The Black Lung Theatre]\n* [http://www.monki.com.au/SAVAGES/SAVAGES.html Savages]\n\n{{EquityAward TVMiniSeriesTeleMovieCast 2010\u20132019}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wright, Thomas M.}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Australian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Australian male child actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name           = Thomas M. Wright\n| image          = ThomasMwright.jpg\n| caption        = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1983|6|22}}\n| birth_place    = [[Melbourne]], Australia\n| death_date     = \n| birth_name     = Thomas Michael Wright\n| years_active   = 1998\u2013present\n| other_names    = Thomas M. Wright\n| occupation     = Actor, producer, writer, director, theatre designer\n| spouse         =\n}}\n'''Thomas Michael Wright''' (born 22 June 1983) is an Australian actor, writer, director and producer. He is the director of the feature film ''Acute Misfortune'' and the co-founder and director of theatre company Black Lung. As an actor he came to attention in [[Jane Campion]]'s series ''[[Top of the Lake]]'', for which he was nominated for Best Supporting Actor at the US Critics Choice Awards.<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/big-bang-theory-unbeatable-as-aussies-sink-at-tv-critics-awards-20130612-2o32f.html</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWright was born June 22, 1983 in [[Melbourne]], the eldest of three children.{{cn|date=February 2019}}\n\n==Career==\nWright is the director, co-writer and producer of the feature film ''Acute Misfortune'', based on Erik Jensen's biography of Australian artist [[Adam Cullen]].<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/books/erik-jensens-biography-of-flawed-artist-adam-cullen-wins-sydney-literary-award-20151124-gl66v0.html</ref> The film debuted at the [[Melbourne International Film Festival]], where it was the winner of ''The Age'' Critic's Award for Best Australian Feature Film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://miff.com.au/program/film/acute-misfortune|title=Acute Misfortune|website=MIFF|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-08-24}}</ref>.  The film received a five star review in The Guardian<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/aug/04/acute-misfortune-first-look-review-adam-cullen-biopic-is-an-enthralling-complex-triumph</ref> and was named one of the best films of 2018 in The Monthly Awards<ref>https://www.themonthly.com.au/issue/2018/october/1538316000/monthly-awards-2018/2018</ref> and by Screen Daily.<ref>https://www.screendaily.com/features/films-of-the-year-2018-sarah-ward/5135405.article</ref> [[Hollywood Reporter|The Hollywood Reporter]] called Acute Misfortune 'one of the year's most striking and accomplished directorial debuts'<ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/acute-misfortune-1135575</ref>. The score, by [[Evelyn Morris|Evelyn Ida Morris]], was nominated for best soundtrack at the 2018 [[ARIA awards|ARIA Awards]]<ref>https://www.ariaawards.com.au/news/2018/2018-aria-award-nominees-announced</ref> and the film was nominated for the 2019 AACTA Award for Best Independent Film<ref>https://www.aacta.org/aacta-awards/winners-and-nominees/</ref>. ''Acute Misfortune'' was named one of The Guardian's [https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/dec/10/from-animal-kingdom-to-the-babadook-the-best-australian-films-of-the-decade 10 Best Australian Films of the decade 2010-2020] and [https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/dec/16/from-the-final-quarter-to-judy-punch-the-best-australian-films-of-2019 the best Australian film of 2019]<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/dec/16/from-the-final-quarter-to-judy-punch-the-best-australian-films-of-2019</ref>.\n\nAs an actor, Wright came to attention in the Sundance / BBC series ''Top of the Lake'', for which he was nominated for Best Supporting Actor at the US Critics' Choice Awards.<ref name=smh2013>{{cite web | title=Big Bang Theory unbeatable as Aussies sink at TV Critics' awards | website=The Sydney Morning Herald | date=12 June 2013 | url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/big-bang-theory-unbeatable-as-aussies-sink-at-tv-critics-awards-20130612-2o32f.html | access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=variety2013>{{cite web | title=Critics\u2019 Choice TV Awards Announced \u2013 Variety | website=Variety | url=https://variety.com/2013/tv/awards/bcta-1200486013/ | access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> Regarding his casting as Johnno Mitcham in the series, director Jane Campion compared him to a young Daniel Day Lewis.<ref>https://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/actor-tom-wright-is-at-the-top-of-his-game-with-jane-campion-television-project/news-story/0e3d8f493da8ec1c09ced262b758f396}}</ref> In 2018 he featured in Warwick Thornton's ''Sweet Country'', which received the Venice Film Festival Special Jury Prize, the AACTA Award for Best Film and The Toronto Film Festival Platform Prize<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/sweet-country-dominates-aacta-awards-with-a-surprise-best-actor-win-20181204-p50k25.html</ref>.\n\nWright featured in the film ''[[The Man with the Iron Heart (film)|The Man With The Iron Heart]]'', an adaptation of Laurent Binet's [[HHhH|Prix De Goncourt winning novel]], with Jack O\u2019Connell, Stephen Graham and Jason Clarke.<ref>https://cineuropa.org/film/330810/</ref> He also filmed the Sony / WGN America Series ''Outsiders'' in the lead role of Sheriff Wade Houghton for producers Peter Tolan and Paul Giamatti. His performance was cited as the standout of the series by ''Hollywood Reporter''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/reviews/outsiders-review-wgn-america-david-morse-1201677147/|title=TV Review: \u2018Outsiders\u2019|last=Lowry|first=Brian|website=Variety|language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> and ''Variety''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/outsiders-tv-review-859145|title='Outsiders': TV Review|website=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIn 2015, Wright filmed the Universal / Working Title feature ''[[Everest (2015 film)|Everest]]'', based on the 1996 \u2018Into Thin Air\u2019 tragedy. Years before the film, Wright walked for a month in the Himalayas on his own, without a porter or guide, crossing the highest mountain pass in the world. He walked for 30 days and lost sixteen kilograms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bbc.co.uk/|title=BBC - Home|website=bbc.co.uk|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> He appeared as cult-figure Steven Linder in the US adaptation of ''[[The Bridge (2013 TV series)|The Bridge]]''. Executive Producer Elwood Reid said of Wright\u2019s audition for the series \u2018it was the best audition I have ever seen. He walked in and the temperature of the room changed.\u2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/entertainment/a/17835120/aussie-actor-wright-repulses-us-producer/|title=Aussie actor Wright repulses US producer|website=au.news.yahoo.com|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> He also played the murdered journalist Brian Peters in ''[[Balibo (film)|Balibo]]'' (2009), and Thomas Bodenham in [[Van Diemen's Land (film)|Van Diemen's Land]].<ref>http://theatrenotes.blogspot.com/2009/03/review-van-diemans-land.html</ref>\n\nWright has played lead roles for the [[Malthouse Theatre]], Melbourne Theatre Company and Sydney Theatre Company, including the title role Baal in the controversial production commissioned by Artistic Directors Cate Blanchett and Andrew Upton and directed by Simon Stone.<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/theatre/baal-20110512-1ekm1.html</ref>\n\nWright created Black Lung in 2006, with fellow writer and director [[Thomas Henning]]. Black Lung were acclaimed{{by whom?|date=March 2019}} for their anarchic process and performance style.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.realtimearts.net/article/74/8185|title=RealTime Arts - Magazine -  issue 74 - The sweet breath of The Black Lung|website=www.realtimearts.net|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref> and hailed as one of the most influential theatre companies of the decade.<ref>https://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/now-for-something-different/news-story/fdd1f8e39838afe6bccb9d26d7152d9e</ref> Under the Black Lung banner, Wright created productions with [[Adelaide Festival]] and [[Darwin Festival]], [[Belvoir (theatre company)|Belvoir]], Malthouse Theatre, and [[Queensland Theatre Company|Queensland Theatre Co.]] and [[Brisbane Festival]].{{cn|date=March 2019}}\n\nWright was the director, co-writer and production designer of ''Doku Rai,'' a production created over four and a half years, with a three-month rehearsal process on the remote island of Atauro, East Timor. ''Doku Rai'' came about after Wright formed a close relationship with Michael Stone, then Chief Military Advisor to the President of Timor, [[Jos\u00e9 Ramos-Horta]]. Stone facilitated Wright flying in and out of the country over a number of years. ''Doku Rai'' was created with a group of independent Timorese artists, a number of them former resistance fighters. The film sequences in ''Doku Rai'' were co-directed by Wright with director Amiel Courtin-Wilson.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/movies/from-the-wild-zone-20120810-23z2m.html|title=From the wild zone {{!}} Doku Rai at Arts House {{!}} Amiel Courtin-Wilson|last=Power|first=Liza|date=2012-08-11|newspaper=The Age|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/booksandarts/actor-director-thomas-m-wright-and-doku-rai/4964826|title=Actor and director Thomas M Wright and 'Doku Rai|website=Radio National|language=en-AU|access-date=2016-04-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Wright was the subject of an Archibald Prize finalist portrait by Marcus Wills, 'Antagonist / Protagonist (Thomas M. Wight)'.<ref>https://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/prizes/archibald/2017/29858/</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n|2000 || [[Stepsister from Planet Weird]] || Cutter Colburne\n|-\n| 2001 || ''[[Zenon: The Zequel]]'' || Orion\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[The King (2007 film)|The King]]'' || Alfie\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Van Diemen's Land (film)|Van Diemen's Land]]'' || Thomas Bodenham\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Balibo (film)|Balibo]]'' || Brian Peters\n|-\n| 2010 || ''Torn'' || Tim Strauss\n|-\n| 2015 || [[Everest (2015 film)|''Everest'']] || [[Michael Groom (climber)|Michael Groom]]\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[The Man with the Iron Heart (film)|The Man with the Iron Heart]]'' || [[Josef Valcik]]\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Sweet Country (2017 film)|Sweet Country]]'' || Mick Kennedy\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Top of the Lake]]'' || Johnno Mitcham\n|-\n| 2013\u20132015 || ''[[The Bridge (2013 TV series)|The Bridge]]'' || Steven Linder\n|-\n| 2016\u20132017 || ''[[Outsiders (TV series)|Outsiders]]'' || Sheriff Wade Houghton\n|}\n\n===Stage===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2004 || ''51 Ashworth St.'' || The Boy || Co-writer, co-director, designer\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Hamlet]]'' || Laertes || Beggars Theatre\n|-\n| 2007 || ''The Glass Soldier'' || Jonas Fink ||  Melbourne Theatre Company\n|-\n| 2007 || ''Pimms'' || Dying Man || Writer, co-director<br />The Black Lung Theatre\n|-\n| 2008 || ''Love Song'' || Beane || Melbourne Theatre Company\n|-\n| 2008 || ''Avast I'' || The Older Brother || Malthouse Theatre\n|-\n| 2008 || ''Avast II'' || Jack Lemmon || Co-director, designer<br />Malthouse Theatre\n|-\n| 2009 || ''Glasson'' || God || The Black Lung Theatre\n|-\n| 2010 || ''Furious Mattress'' || The Exorcist || Malthouse Theatre\n|-\n| 2011 || ''Baal'' || Baal || Sydney Theatre Company\n|-\n| 2011 || ''And They Called Him Mr. Glamour'' || || Director, designer<br />Belvoir St. Theatre\n|-\n| 2011 || ''I Feel Awful'' || || Writer, director, designer<br />Brisbane Festival\n|-\n| 2013 || ''Doku Rai'' || || Co-writer, director, designer<br />The Black Lung Theatre\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{iMDb name|0942876}}\n* [http://www.theblacklung.com The Black Lung Theatre]\n* [http://www.monki.com.au/SAVAGES/SAVAGES.html Savages]\n\n{{EquityAward TVMiniSeriesTeleMovieCast 2010\u20132019}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wright, Thomas M.}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Australian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Australian male child actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian male actors]]\n", "name_user": "Laterthanyouthink", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:oops wrong Henning", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Wright_(Australian_actor)"}
